Η. Cratippum] An eminent Peripatetic philosopher, born at Mitylene, where he consoled Pompey aiter his llight from the battle oi Pharsalia (Plutarch a. Pancp. p. 659 c. 75). When Cicero visited Cilicia, Cratippus met him at Ephesus and obtained through his intercession with Caesar the Roman franchise. On coming to Athens he was requested, at the instance also of Cicero, by the Areopagites to open a school there (Plutarch a. Cicer. p. 873 c. 24). He wrote a treatise de damnatione and saacaiomm interpretatione (Cic. de dia. 1 c. 3, 11 c. 48 sqq., Tertullian de areium 11 c. 46).
